As discussed in the previous problem, the equivalent annual cost is the method of comparing two assets or equipment that have different lifespans. In order to solve this, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent annual cost}&=\dfrac{\text{Net present value}}{\text{Annuity factor}}
\end{aligned}$$

For the net present value, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=(\text{Annual cost} \times \text{Annuity factor})-\text{Initial price}
\end{aligned}$$

Now, for the annual cost, we will simply multiply the annual watts of each bulb to the cost. However, since we are solving for the break-even cost, then this will still be a variable. 

For the **incandescent light bulb**:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Annual cost}&=30 \times \text{cost}
\end{aligned}$$

For the **LED light bulb**:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Annual cost}&=0.0875 \times \text{cost}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the known values to the formula in Step 3, we will get the following:

For the **incandescent light bulb**:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent annual cost}&=\dfrac{(30 \times \text{cost} \times 1.7355)-\$0.45}{1.7355}
\end{aligned}$$

For the **LED light bulb**:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent annual cost}&=\dfrac{(0.0875 \times \text{cost} \times 9.99512)-\$2.25}{9.99512}
\end{aligned}$$

To get the break-even price per kilowatt-hour, we will simply equate these two:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(30 \times \text{cost} \times 1.7355)-\$0.45}{1.7355}&=\dfrac{(0.0875 \times \text{cost} \times 9.99512)-\$2.25}{9.99512}
\end{aligned}$$

Simplifying the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(52.065\times \text{cost})-\$0.45}{1.7355}&=\dfrac{(0.874573 \times \text{cost})-\$2.25}{9.99512}
\end{aligned}$$
